Spawnpoints.

A spawnpoint marks where the player appears on a map. When a map loads, the player is placed at a spawnpoint; and when the player walks over one during play, it becomes their active spawn, so a later reload drops them back there rather than at the start. It's the entity for setting a map's opening position and for moving that position forward as the player makes progress. A spawnpoint is silent and has nothing to configure but its location.

A spawnpoint is the appearance marker. Its sibling, the checkpoint, is the death-recovery marker that returns the player to a spot after a fatal hit; see the checkpoints topic for that side of the same idea.

How a spawnpoint works.

A spawnpoint sits on a single tile. It makes no sound and does nothing as the player passes over it except quietly become the active spawn. When a map loads fresh — a new visit, a retry, or a reload — the player appears at the spawnpoint they most recently stepped on. If they haven't stepped on any yet, they appear at the first spawnpoint placed in the map.

Because stepping on a spawnpoint updates the active spawn without using it up, you can line several across a map and the player's reappearance point advances as they walk past each one — so a long map doesn't send the player all the way back to the entrance after every reload.

How spawnpoints differ from checkpoints.

The two are easy to confuse, so the distinction is worth stating plainly:

A spawnpoint governs where the player appears when the map loads. It's silent, reusable, and updates as the player walks over each one.
A checkpoint governs where the player returns after a fatal hit on their last life. It announces itself with sound and is claimed (and consumed) when touched.

Place spawnpoints to set and advance the starting position; place checkpoints to give the player a death-recovery net.

Spawnpoint fields.

The spawnpoint form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and y (and z on 3d maps) — the tile where the player appears.

A spawnpoint has no sound and no other settings; its location is the whole of its configuration.

Authoring spawnpoints by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a spawnpoint is: spawnpoint x y. On 3d maps a z follows y: spawnpoint x y z. There are no other fields — the line is nothing but the entity name and its position.
